div.p:
But I (my Brethren) endeuouring my selfe, (according to my place and calling) to be acquainted as well with your dispositions, and inclinations, as with your persons, (that so I might know the better, how to giue euery one his portion, and that in due season) perceiue plainely among you, a very great difference. And although it bee not my office to looke into any mans heart, but as the words of his

 mouth, and the actions of his life doe discouer the same, and make it apparant: Neither am able, (if it were fit) to take a particular view, of the priuate and particular demeanour of euery one: Yet, if I be asked, how well I can call my Sheepe by their names;
                  Ioh. 10.3. and what is the estate and condition of this little flocke: I speake it in the presence of God, (for I am so perswaded in my conscience, and finde by experience) that as there are some few amongst you truely fearing God, endeuouring to approue their hearts and liues vnto God, and to manifest that grace that is wrought in them, by the fruits of grace, & who desire (in the vse of such ordinary meanes as the Lord hath appointed) to grow, and flourish, as greene Gardens, and as Trees planted by the Riuers of waters, in all the graces of sanctification, not only for their owne peculiar good, and for the sure sealing of their owne saluation; but also

 for the good & saluation of others, according to their places and callings, and that measure of spirituall gifts which they haue receiued:

Thus we may sée how rightly the Papists agree with the Capernaits, Ioh. 6. For euen as they imagined, that Christ would giue his very flesh and bloud to bée eaten and drunke with the bodily mouth, as other meat and drinke: and therefore contended among themselues, saying, How can this man giue vs his flesh to eate?

                        Ioh. 6.52.60.63. And thereupon went away offended, saying;


                     This is an hard saying, who can heare it? Euen so doe the Papists gather, and conclude vpon the very same words of Christ at this day. But as our Lord Iesus Christ, to correct the erroneous conceit of the Capernaites, said vnto them, that his words are spirit, and life, that is to say, figuratiuely spoken, and spiritually to bee vnderstood: euen so is the same our answere to the Papists at this day, that we are ingrafted into Christ, and doe truely eate his flesh, and drinke his bloud, but yet onely after a spirituall manner, and no otherwise then by faith.


                       Exod. 20.12.As he alone is a good child, that is duly obedient to the lawfull commandements of his Parents;
                       Col. 3.22. hee onely a good seruant, that serueth his Master, not with eye seruice, but in singlenesse of heart; and hee onely a true and faithfull Subiect,
                       Rom. 13.1. which yeeldeth himselfe obedient, and conformable to the godly lawes, and commandements of his naturall Prince and Gouernour: euen so are such onely, and none but such worthy the name, and account of Gods elect and chosen Saints, to whom belongeth the inheritance of eternall life,

who are religiously obedient, and conformable to the holy will and commandements of the Lord God;

And whereas the Euangelist Luke, describing the celebration of the Passeouer, and the institution of the Sacrament, in a whole narratiō, addeth these words of the Lord;
                        Luke 22.21
                     Yet behold the hand of him that betrayeth me, is with me at the table: we haue no warrant to vnderstand this of Iudas his presence at this Sacrament, because it is out of all controuersie, that Luke differeth not from the other Euangelist. There is, and must be an harmony betwixt them, which harmony and consent they must deny, who gather vpon Luke, that Iudas receiued the Sacrament of the Lords Supper with the rest.
